[h1]Creating Arrays [/h1]

You can also declare an array, tell it the number of elements it will store, and add the elements later.[code format="js" codeId="696"]var courses = new Array([b]3[/b]);
courses[0] = "HTML";
courses[1] = "CSS";
courses[2] = "JS";[/code]
[note]An array is a special type of [b]object[/b].
An array uses [b]numbers [/b]to access its elements, and an object uses [b]names [/b]to access its members. [/note]

[h1]Creating Arrays[/h1]

JavaScript arrays are dynamic, so you can declare an array and not pass any arguments with the Array() constructor. You can then add the elements dynamically.[code format="js" codeId="695"]var courses = new Array[b]()[/b];
courses[0] = "HTML";
courses[1] = "CSS";
courses[2] = "JS";
courses[3] = "C++";[/code]
[note]You can add as many elements as you need to.[/note]
[h2]Array Literal[/h2]

For greater simplicity, readability, and execution speed, you can also declare arrays using the [b]array literal[/b] syntax.[code format="js" codeId="697"]var courses = ["HTML", "CSS", "JS"]; [/code]
This results in the same array as the one created with the [b]new Array()[/b] syntax. 
[note]You can access and modify the elements of the array using the index number, as you did before.
The [b]array literal[/b] syntax is the recommended way to declare arrays.[/note]
